doc.title: 2026 spending outlook: Navigating growth amidst shifting consumer dynamics
doc.source_uri: 2025-09-02/2026 spending outlook_ Navigating growth amidst shifting consumer dynamics_2025-09-02

passages.text: On September \(3^{\mathrm{rd}}\) and \(4^{\mathrm{th}}\) we will host \(\sim 85\) consumer companies at our \(32^{\mathrm{nd}}\) annual Global Retailing Conference, where we expect to hear updates on the US consumer, shopping behavior through back- to- school and ahead of the holidays, and views on tariffs and pricing. (See here for agenda and registration). We expect the messaging to be cautious around the health of the consumer and macro uncertainties into the back half of 2025. However, while there continue to be concerns around the spending behavior, we remain cautiously optimistic going into 2026. We expect an improvement in disposable personal income growth, which, coupled with the potential benefit from easing interest rates and moderating essential spending should drive an improvement in discretionary cash inflow for consumers into next year.

With this report, we mark to market our 2025 forecasts, and introduce our 2026 US consumer discretionary cash flow (DCF) model on the back of our economists' 2026 disposable personal income forecasts (see here). Our economists expect real disposable personal income growth to improve in 2026 from 2025, driven by a pickup in job growth, fading inflation from tariffs, and a moderate fiscal boost at the start of next year. Furthermore, as we layer this into our discretionary cash flow (DCF), we expect an improvement in total household cash flow growth in 2026 of \(+4.2\%\) , up from \(+3.8\%\) in 2025, based on slightly higher mortgage equity withdrawals and borrowings in an easing interest rate environment. This, along with moderating financial obligations as well as more modest outlays for essential spending should support pre- savings DCF growth of \(+4.6\%\) in 2026, up from \(+3.8\%\) in 2025. That said, we note that this remains below the \(+5.4\%\) average pre- Covid (i.e., 2009- 19) growth levels. In addition, our economists expect a roughly \(4.9\%\) savings rate (as a \(\%\) of income), which could also provide support for possible acceleration in spending growth for 2026, as is illustrated in our savings- adjusted discretionary cash flow forecast of \(+4.1\%\) , up from \(+3.8\%\) in 2025.

Overall, we have seen growing concerns around the health of the US consumer and more value- seeking spending behavior, especially amongst the lowest income cohorts, as has been indicated by management commentary and a step- up in promotional activity by CPG manufacturers. However, we expect a combination of

job growth, easing interest rates, and more benign essential spending to translate into resilient spending power across some quintiles, with low- to- mid single digit growth in pre- savings DCF across all income quintiles over the next year based on our economists' forecasts. Further, we expect growth to be skewed toward the middle income quintiles as they benefit from SALT, no tax on tips or overtime, and interest deductibility on auto loans, while lower income quintiles will face headwinds from cuts in Medicaid and SNAP benefits.

HundredX data suggests accelerating net purchase intent: Our analysis suggests overall net purchase intent accelerated meaningfully in August following weaker trends in late June and early July. Within this, purchase intent across each of the consumer sectors contributed to this improvement, though we have seen a shift in trends by income demographic with purchase intent for the lowest income consumers stronger than all other income cohorts in June, deteriorated materially in July, and has been trending lower than all other income cohorts in August MTD. In contrast, purchase intent trends for the highest income consumer have accelerated the most meaningfully in July/August.

As we look to 2026, this would lead us to continue to favor more discretionary led categories within our coverage universe, but remain positive on certain staples names. In that vein we highlight Buy rated ULTA, OLLI, HD, KTB, AS, SN, MNST, PM, PEP, SFM, EAT, MCD, and SHAK, as stocks to own as 2026 approaches, while we highlight Sell rated AAP, CROX, CLX, CAG, and JACK where we believe topline growth could be pressured.

Our economists expect real spending growth to remain soft in 2H25 as higher inflation erodes real consumer spending power. In terms of employment, our economists now expect an unemployment rate of \(4.4\%\) by the end of 2025 due to a slower pace of immigration, fading tailwinds from catch- up hiring and continued declines in job openings. Moreover, our economists expect that higher inflation and slower job growth will weigh on real income in 2H25, with underperformance among the bottom and top income quintiles. Consumer credit growth remained soft in June, with credit card delinquency rates continuing to level off through 2Q25. In addition, aggregate household balance sheets remain strong, with an elevated net worth to DPI ratio. Moreover, the savings rate remains broadly in line with levels consistent with economic fundamentals (i.e., healthy household balance sheets and labor market), and our economists forecast

that the saving rate will remain at \(4.5\%\) through 2025- end. That said, our economists highlighted that all consumer confidence and sentiment measures remain low due to uncertainty over the policy and inflation outlook.

Overall, based on our economists' forecasts, we now expect 2025 DPI growth to be 30bps higher at \(+4.5\%\) , relative to our previous forecast (as of May 2025) of \(+4.2\%\) , which reflects an expansion in DPI growth expectations across income quintiles (an increase of \(\sim 60\) bps on average for the bottom three quintiles and 20 bps on average for the top two quintiles). Notably, this translates to a 15bps higher pre- savings DCF growth forecast for 2025 to \(+3.8\%\) (vs. \(+3.6\%\) as of May 2025), with the highest expansion seen in the bottom two quintiles. To summarize, we now model \(+2.2\% / + 3.7\% / + 4.2\% / + 3.9\% / + 3.8\%\) pre- savings DCF growth across bottom/2nd/3rd/4th/top quintiles respectively, compared to \(+1.6\% / + 3.0\% / + 3.9\% / + 4.0\% / + 3.7\%\) previously (as of May 2025), which follows \(+2.5\% / + 3.5\% / + 2.2\% / + 4.6\% / + 4.8\%\) pre- savings DCF growth in 2024.

As we draw towards the close of 3Q25, investor focus has increasingly shifted toward 2026 and the health of the consumer to better understand the spending outlook. In that vein, we mark to market our 2025 discretionary cash flow model and introduce our 2026 outlook for consumers in aggregate and by income quintiles. Our economists expect income growth to pick up next year, driven by a pick up in job growth and the receding inflationary impact of tariffs. Based on our economists' forecasts, we expect \(+4.7\%\) DPI

growth in 2026, following \(+4.5\%\) DPI growth in 2025, which marks a modest sequential acceleration and is ahead of historical levels (i.e., 2009- 2019 average annual growth of \(4.0\%\) ), with modest sequential acceleration in 2H26 to exit the year closer to \(4.8\%\) growth rate.

We expect this to translate into a slight sequential improvement in net household cash inflow as well, to \(+4.2\%\) in 2026, from \(+3.8\%\) in 2025. Elevated interest rates were a meaningful burden on the US consumer in 2025, but our economists expect two rate cuts in 2026, following three 25bp cuts in September, October, and December in 2025. Therefore, we now model only a modest benefit going into 2026, including mortgage equity withdrawals (MEW) to \(- \$ 119bn\) (vs. \(94bn\) in 2025) and in borrowings to \(- \$ 95bn\) (vs. \(94bn\) in 2025). In addition, we expect financial obligations to see a slight down tick later in 2025 and into 2026, as we anticipate modest relief from a more favorable interest rate environment; we expect financial obligations to be \(14.3\%\) of DPI in 2026, compared to \(14.5\%\) of DPI in 2025.

Moreover, we expect essential expenditure growth to moderate to \(+3.3\%\) in 2026, from \(+3.7\%\) in 2025, as it benefits from decelerating growth in healthcare costs and slight easing in energy costs along with largely stable (albeit elevated relative to 2023- 24 levels) food spending for the year. This, coupled with modest DPI growth translates into \(+4.6\%\) discretionary cash inflow growth in 2026, a sequential improvement compared to \(+3.8\%\) growth in 2025. Based on our economists' forecast, we expect the savings rate in 2026 to be higher compared to 2025 levels, but still enough to support a slight sequential improvement in adjusted DCF (which is a proxy for PCE) for 2026 to \(+4.1\%\) vs. \(+3.8\%\) in 2025.
Exhibit 23: We expect \(+4.7\%\) DPI growth to translate to \(+4.6\%\) discretionary cash inflow in 2026, which should support \(+4.1\%\) adj. DCF growth in the year in $bn
Source: BEA, BLS, Federal Reserve, EIA, CMS, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

By quintile, we expect 2026 DPI growth to be skewed toward the middle income quintiles (i.e., \(\sim 5\%\) YoY) as these quintiles benefit from SALT, no tax on tips or overtime and interest deductibility on auto loans. This flows through to robust pre- savings DCF growth as well, up \(+5.1\% / + 4.9\%\) (vs. \(+4.2\% / + 3.9\%\) in 2025) for third/fourth quintiles

respectively. And while the low income quintile lags, we still expect it to post resilient \(+4.3\%\) YoY DPI growth in 2026. Coupled with a more subdued essential spending pressure and likely easing financial obligations (albeit still elevated compared to historical levels), we expect relatively resilient DPI growth to translate to \(+3.1\% / + 4.3\% / + 5.1\% / + 4.9\% / + 4.6\%\) (vs. \(+2.2\% / + 3.7\% / + 4.2\% / + 3.9\% / + 3.8\%\) in 2025) pre- savings DCF growth across bottom/2nd/3rd/4th/top quintiles respectively.

We supplement our DCF work with data from HundredX, a mission- based data and insights company that takes an innovative approach to monitoring consumer perceptions and gathering consumer feedback to understand trends across \(80+\) industries and \(3,000+\) brands. HundredX analyzes collective opinions of everyday customers and evaluates how their priorities influence purchasing decisions and attitudes toward businesses and brands.

On balance, our analysis suggests net purchase intent accelerated meaningfully in August following choppier trends in late June and early July. Within this, purchase intent across each of the consumer sectors we track contributed to this improvement, though we have seen a shift in trends by income demographic. Here, we note purchase intent for the lowest income consumers was stronger than all other income cohorts in June, deteriorated materially in July, and has been trending lower than all other income cohorts in August MTD. In contrast, purchase intent trends for the highest income consumer have accelerated the most meaningfully in July/August. Notably, overall purchase intent trends have improved despite weakening consumer perceptions of price and value across the marketplace.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.

Being assigned a Buy or Sell on an Investment List is determined by a stock's total return potential relative to its coverage universe. Any stock not assigned as a Buy or a Sell on an Investment List with an active rating (i.e., a stock that is not Rating Suspended, Not Rated, Early- Stage Biotech, Coverage Suspended or Not Covered), is deemed Neutral. Each region manages Regional Conviction Lists, which are selected from Buy rated stocks on the respective region's Investment Lists and represent investment recommendations focused on the size of the total return potential and/or the likelihood of the realization of the return across their respective areas of coverage. The addition or removal of stocks from such Conviction Lists are managed by the Investment Review Committee or other designated committee in each respective region and do not represent a change in the analysts' investment rating for such stocks.

Total return potential represents the upside or downside differential between the current share price and the price target, including all paid or anticipated dividends, expected during the time horizon associated with the price target. Price targets are required for all covered stocks. The total return potential, price target and associated time horizon are stated in each report adding or reiterating an Investment List membership.
